      "source": [
        "3. If the training data is highly unbalanced, is `accuracy` a good metric for the classifiers' performance? Does a high accuracy necessarily means a high f1-score? Compare `accuracy` with `f1-score`. Based on your criterion, which type of classifier is better? Please give some justifications to support your answer.\n",
        "\n",
        "For highly unbalanced data, accuracy is not a good metric for performance. If given a set with very low spam percentages, a model that only guesses ham will have high accuracy, but will completely fail to ever spot a spam. A high accuracy does not always equal a high f1 score. I think that f1 is a better metric because it involves alot more things, and also gives more weight to costly mistakes, like failed spam detection."
